Searching Algorithms – Summary
Introduction
Searching is the process of finding the location of a specific element in a data structure.
It is one of the fundamental operations in Data Structures and Algorithms.
The two most common searching algorithms are Linear Search and Binary Search.
1. Linear Search
Checks each element one by one until the target element is found or the list ends.
Works with both sorted and unsorted data.
Easy to implement but inefficient for large datasets.

Time Complexity

Best Case: O(1) (element found at the first position)
Average Case: O(n)
Worst Case: O(n) (element found at the last position or not found)
2. Binary Search
Repeatedly divides the search space into two halves to find the target element.
Requires the data to be sorted before searching.
Much faster than linear search for large datasets.

Time Complexity

Best Case: O(1) (element found at the middle)
Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case: O(log n)
Comparison of Searching Algorithms
Feature	Linear Search	Binary Search
Data Requirement	Sorted or Unsorted	Sorted only
Searching Method	Sequential search	Divide and conquer
Best Case	O(1)	O(1)
Average Case	O(n)	O(log n)
Worst Case	O(n)	O(log n)
Advantages

Linear Search

Simple to implement.
Works on both sorted and unsorted data.
Suitable for small datasets.

Binary Search

Very fast for large sorted datasets.
Reduces the search space by half in each step.
More efficient than linear search for large inputs.
Disadvantages

Linear Search

Slow for large datasets.
Checks elements one by one.

Binary Search

Works only on sorted data.
Sorting may add extra overhead if the data is initially unsorted.

Applications

Linear Search: Small datasets, unsorted arrays, linked lists.
Binary Search: Large sorted arrays, databases, dictionaries, searching in sorted files.

Key Points

Linear Search scans elements sequentially and has O(n) worst-case time complexity.
Binary Search uses the divide-and-conquer technique and has O(log n) worst-case time complexity.
Binary Search is preferred for large, sorted datasets, while Linear Search is suitable for small or unsorted datasets.